{
  "executive_summary": "Architecture for a real-time ML delivery time estimation service with a clean separation between the serving path (latency-critical, called at checkout) and the training path (batch, weekly). The design optimizes for the 100ms P99 constraint by using a lightweight model served from memory behind a thin API, with a blue-green model deployment strategy for safe rollbacks. Sized for a 4-person team — avoids Kubernetes/Kubeflow complexity in favor of simple, operable components.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction API",
        "responsibility": "Serves real-time delivery time predictions. Loads the active model into memory on startup. Stateless — horizontally scalable. Exposes a single POST /predict endpoint.",
        "boundaries": "Owns only inference. No training logic, no data collection. Reads model artifacts from Model Registry. Health check reports model version and latency percentiles."
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Store",
        "responsibility": "Provides consistent feature computation for both training and serving. Online store (Redis) for low-latency serving features (current courier load, live weather). Offline store (Parquet/S3) for historical training features.",
        "boundaries": "Owns feature definitions and transformations. Single source of truth for feature logic — eliminates training/serving skew. Does not own raw event data."
      },
      {
        "name": "Training Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Weekly batch job that pulls historical delivery data, computes training features from the offline store, trains a new model (gradient-boosted trees — LightGBM/XGBoost), evaluates against holdout set, and publishes a candidate model to the Model Registry.",
        "boundaries": "Owns model training and offline evaluation only. Does not decide whether the model goes live — that is the Model Registry + promotion gate's job."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Registry",
        "responsibility": "Versioned storage of model artifacts with metadata (metrics, training date, dataset hash, status). Supports statuses: candidate, active, rolled-back. Exactly one model is 'active' at any time. Previous 'active' becomes 'rollback-ready'.",
        "boundaries": "Owns model lifecycle state. Does not serve predictions. Implemented as S3 bucket + DynamoDB/Postgres metadata table. No ML framework dependency."
      },
      {
        "name": "Promotion Gate",
        "responsibility": "Automated quality gate that compares candidate model against the active model on holdout metrics (MAE, P95 error, bias by zone). If candidate passes thresholds, promotes to active. If not, alerts team and leaves current model in place.",
        "boundaries": "Owns promotion policy. Can be overridden manually by ML engineers. Shadow-mode traffic comparison is a future enhancement, not required for V1."
      },
      {
        "name": "Data Collector",
        "responsibility": "Captures actual delivery completion events and enriches them with the features that were used at prediction time (logged by Prediction API). Writes to the training dataset in the offline store.",
        "boundaries": "Owns ground-truth label collection. Async — does not affect serving latency. Implemented as a consumer off an event queue."
      },
      {
        "name": "Monitoring & Alerting",
        "responsibility": "Tracks prediction latency (P50/P95/P99), model accuracy drift (predicted vs actual delivery time), feature distribution drift, and error rates. Triggers rollback alert if accuracy degrades beyond threshold post-deployment.",
        "boundaries": "Read-only observation layer. Does not mutate model state, but can trigger a PagerDuty/Slack alert that leads to manual or automated rollback."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Checkout Service (external)",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "POST /predict { weight_kg, distance_km, zone_id, order_time_utc } → { estimated_minutes, confidence_interval, model_version }. Timeout budget: 100ms.",
        "coupling_type": "runtime-sync"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Feature Store (Online)",
        "contract": "GET features by (zone_id, order_time_utc) → { weather_code, courier_load, zone_avg_delay }. Must respond in <15ms.",
        "coupling_type": "runtime-sync"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "On startup and on SIGHUP/polling: fetch model artifact for status=active. Model loaded into process memory — no per-request registry call.",
        "coupling_type": "deployment-time"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Data Collector",
        "contract": "Async emit: { prediction_id, features_used, predicted_minutes, model_version, timestamp } → message queue (SQS/Kafka topic).",
        "coupling_type": "async-event"
      },
      {
        "from": "Delivery Completion (external event)",
        "to": "Data Collector",
        "contract": "Event: { order_id, actual_delivery_minutes, completed_at } → joined with prediction log to create labeled training sample.",
        "coupling_type": "async-event"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Feature Store (Offline)",
        "contract": "Read Parquet partitions by date range. Same feature transformation code as online store.",
        "coupling_type": "batch-read"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "PUT model artifact + metadata { version, metrics, dataset_hash, status=candidate }.",
        "coupling_type": "batch-write"
      },
      {
        "from": "Promotion Gate",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "UPDATE status: candidate→active, previous active→rollback-ready. Atomic swap.",
        "coupling_type": "batch-write"
      },
      {
        "from": "Monitoring & Alerting",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "Scrape /metrics endpoint (Prometheus format): request_latency_ms, prediction_value histogram, model_version gauge.",
        "coupling_type": "pull-observe"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "REQUEST PATH: Checkout → Prediction API → (Feature Store Online for dynamic features) → in-memory model inference → response. Latency budget: 15ms feature fetch + 5ms inference + 10ms network overhead = ~30ms typical, well within 100ms P99. TRAINING PATH: Delivery events + prediction logs → Data Collector → Offline Feature Store → Training Pipeline (weekly cron) → Model Registry (candidate) → Promotion Gate (eval) → Model Registry (active) → Prediction API picks up new model. FEEDBACK LOOP: Prediction API logs every prediction with features used. Data Collector joins with actual delivery time to create labeled samples. This closes the loop for retraining.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Blue-Green Model Deployment",
        "rationale": "Exactly one model is active. Previous model is retained as rollback-ready. Rollback is a metadata flip (active↔rollback-ready) — no redeployment needed. Prediction API polls or receives signal to hot-swap the in-memory model."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Feature Store (Online/Offline Split)",
        "rationale": "Eliminates training/serving skew — the #1 silent killer in ML systems. Shared feature transformation code ensures the model sees the same features in production as in training. Online store (Redis) meets latency requirements; offline store (Parquet) meets training throughput."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Strangler-safe Model Serving (Model-in-Process)",
        "rationale": "Loading LightGBM/XGBoost model directly into API process memory avoids network hop to a separate model server. For a single tabular model, this is far simpler and faster than TensorFlow Serving or Triton. Can evolve to a model server later if model count grows."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Prediction Logging for Label Join",
        "rationale": "Every prediction is logged with the exact features used, enabling accurate label joins and retraining. This is the foundation of the continuous learning loop."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Automated Quality Gate with Manual Override",
        "rationale": "Prevents bad models from reaching production automatically, but allows ML engineers to force-promote or force-rollback. Appropriate for a small team where full automation trust hasn't been established yet."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction Serving",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionRequest (value object: features in, estimate out)", "ModelArtifact (entity: versioned, loaded into memory)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Lifecycle",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["ModelVersion (entity: version, status, metrics, artifact URI)", "PromotionDecision (entity: candidate vs active comparison result)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Management",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["FeatureDefinition (entity: name, transformation, source)", "FeatureVector (value object: computed features for a given context)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Training",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["TrainingRun (entity: dataset version, hyperparams, output model, metrics)", "TrainingDataset (entity: date range, sample count, label distribution)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Data Collection",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionLog (event: features, prediction, timestamp)", "DeliveryOutcome (event: actual time, joined with prediction)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Model Lifecycle publishes model artifacts; Prediction Serving consumes them. Serving team can request specific artifact format but Lifecycle owns the schema."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Management",
        "downstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "relationship": "Shared Kernel — Feature transformation code is shared between online serving and offline training to prevent skew. This coupling is intentional and critical."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Management",
        "downstream": "Training",
        "relationship": "Shared Kernel — Same feature transformation library used in training pipeline."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery Data Collection",
        "downstream": "Training",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Training consumes labeled data in whatever format Data Collection produces."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "downstream": "Delivery Data Collection",
        "relationship": "Published Language — Prediction API emits structured prediction log events that Data Collection consumes."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "LightGBM/XGBoost (gradient-boosted trees) over deep learning",
      "gains": "Sub-5ms inference on tabular data without GPU. Interpretable feature importances. Simple to train, serialize, and load. Two ML engineers can own this fully.",
      "sacrifices": "May miss complex non-linear interactions that a neural net could capture. Less fashionable.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Deep learning (PyTorch) — rejected: requires GPU serving infra, 10-50ms inference, overkill for structured tabular features", "Linear regression — rejected: too simple, poor accuracy on non-linear delivery patterns"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Model-in-process serving over dedicated model server (Triton, TF Serving, Seldon)",
      "gains": "Zero network hop for inference. Trivially simple deployment — just a Python/Rust API with the model loaded. 4-person team cannot afford to operate a model serving platform.",
      "sacrifices": "If model count grows beyond 2-3, this won't scale well. No built-in A/B testing infrastructure.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Triton Inference Server — rejected for V1: operational overhead disproportionate to single-model use case", "BentoML — considered as a middle ground, could be V2 if complexity grows"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Weekly batch retraining over online/continuous learning",
      "gains": "Simple, debuggable, auditable. Training failures don't affect serving. Easy to reason about which data went into which model.",
      "sacrifices": "Model can be up to 7 days stale. Seasonal shifts (e.g., holiday surge) take a week to adapt.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Daily retraining — viable future optimization if staleness becomes a problem", "Online learning — rejected: much harder to debug, validate, and rollback"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Redis for online feature store over embedded cache",
      "gains": "Shared state across Prediction API instances (courier load is global). Sub-5ms reads. Operationally simple.",
      "sacrifices": "Additional infrastructure component. Network hop adds ~2-5ms.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["In-process cache — rejected: courier load and weather are dynamic, shared across instances", "DynamoDB — viable but Redis is faster for simple key-value lookups at this latency requirement"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Metadata-based rollback over full redeployment rollback",
      "gains": "Rollback is a single database update (status flip). Prediction API hot-loads the rollback model within seconds. No CI/CD pipeline needed for rollback.",
      "sacrifices": "Requires Prediction API to implement model hot-swapping logic (adds ~100 lines of code). Two model versions must be loadable in memory during swap.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Git-based rollback with full redeploy — rejected: too slow for incident response, 10+ minutes vs seconds"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Model algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Model-in-process pattern supports any sklearn-compatible model. Can swap LightGBM for XGBoost, CatBoost, or even a small neural net without changing serving infrastructure. Just change the training pipeline and model serialization format."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature set",
      "evolution_path": "Feature Store abstraction means adding new features (e.g., traffic data, courier experience level) requires: (1) add feature definition, (2) add to online/offline store population, (3) retrain. No serving code changes needed."
    },
    {
      "area": "Retraining frequency",
      "evolution_path": "Weekly cron can become daily or triggered-on-drift by simply changing the schedule or adding a drift-detection trigger. Pipeline is idempotent — safe to run more frequently."
    },
    {
      "area": "Multi-model serving",
      "evolution_path": "If the business needs zone-specific models or A/B testing, the Prediction API can load multiple models keyed by zone or experiment ID. The Model Registry already supports multiple versions. Migration to BentoML or Seldon is possible but deferred."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Feature transformation code sharing (Shared Kernel)",
      "reason": "The shared feature transformation library between online serving and offline training is intentionally rigid. Any change must be deployed to both contexts simultaneously. This coupling is the price of preventing training/serving skew, which is far more dangerous than the coupling cost."
    },
    {
      "area": "Synchronous prediction path",
      "reason": "The checkout→predict path is synchronous by nature — the customer is waiting. This constrains model complexity, feature fetch latency, and rules out any async enrichment during inference. This is a hard constraint from the business."
    },
    {
      "area": "Single active model invariant",
      "reason": "Exactly one model is active at any time. This simplifies reasoning about production behavior but means A/B testing requires an explicit extension. Intentionally rigid for V1 to keep rollback semantics simple."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Training/serving skew despite Feature Store",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Enforce shared feature transformation code via a single library imported by both training pipeline and Prediction API. Add integration test that computes features for a fixed input in both online and offline mode and asserts equality."
    },
    {
      "risk": "P99 latency breach under load",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Load test with realistic traffic patterns. Budget: 15ms feature fetch (Redis) + 5ms inference (LightGBM) + 10ms serialization/network = 30ms typical. Headroom to 100ms P99 is 3x. Add circuit breaker: if feature fetch exceeds 50ms, fall back to default features (zone averages cached in-process). Monitor P99 continuously."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Bad model promoted to production",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Promotion Gate compares candidate against active model on holdout set. Require MAE improvement or parity. Add zone-level bias check (model shouldn't systematically over/under-predict for any zone). Rollback is a metadata flip — recovery time < 30 seconds."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Stale features in online store (e.g., courier load not updated)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Feature Store online population is event-driven (courier assignment/completion events update Redis). Add staleness check: if courier_load feature is older than 5 minutes, flag as stale and use zone-level default. Alert on staleness rate > 5%."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Small team stretched across too many components",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "V1 scope is deliberately minimal. Use managed services where possible (S3 for artifacts, managed Redis, SQS for events). 2 ML engineers own Training Pipeline + Feature Store + Promotion Gate. 2 platform engineers own Prediction API + Data Collector + Monitoring. Defer advanced features (A/B testing, shadow mode) until V1 is stable."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Prediction logging impacts serving latency",
      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "Prediction logging is fire-and-forget async (enqueue to SQS/local buffer). If queue is full, drop log entry rather than blocking the response. Acceptable to lose <0.1% of prediction logs."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (Weeks 1-3): Platform engineers build Prediction API with hardcoded heuristic model (distance/weight formula) + Redis feature store + /predict endpoint. ML engineers build training pipeline + offline feature store + model registry (S3 + Postgres). Phase 2 (Weeks 4-5): Integrate — swap heuristic for first trained LightGBM model. Build Promotion Gate. Wire up prediction logging + Data Collector. Phase 3 (Week 6): Monitoring, load testing, rollback drills. Production readiness review. This phasing means checkout integration can start in Week 2 with the heuristic model — no waiting for ML.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "prediction-api/ — FastAPI service: main.py, model_loader.py, feature_client.py, schemas.py",
      "prediction-api/Dockerfile — Slim Python image with LightGBM pre-installed",
      "feature-store/ — Shared feature transformation library: transforms.py, online_client.py, offline_reader.py",
      "training-pipeline/ — Airflow DAG or simple Python script: train.py, evaluate.py, registry_client.py",
      "promotion-gate/ — Evaluation + promotion logic: compare.py, promote.py",
      "data-collector/ — SQS consumer: consumer.py, label_joiner.py",
      "model-registry/ — Thin abstraction over S3 + Postgres: registry.py, models.sql",
      "infra/ — Terraform/CDK for Redis, S3, SQS, ECS/EC2 for API",
      "tests/ — Integration test for feature skew detection, load test script (locust), rollback drill script"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Shared feature library is THE critical architectural element — treat it as a first-class internal package with its own tests. Prediction API must be stateless except for the in-memory model. Use structured logging with prediction_id for end-to-end tracing. Model artifacts must be immutable once written — never overwrite, always version.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT compute features differently in training vs serving — this is the most common ML system failure mode",
      "DO NOT call the model registry on every prediction request — load model into memory at startup and on promotion events only",
      "DO NOT use pickle for model serialization — use LightGBM's native format for safety and portability",
      "DO NOT skip the Promotion Gate for 'quick fixes' — every model goes through the gate, even hotfixes",
      "DO NOT build a Kubernetes-based ML platform — a 4-person team cannot operate it; use ECS or even EC2 with a load balancer",
      "DO NOT log raw customer data in prediction logs — log feature vectors only (already transformed, not PII)"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Model-in-process serving is correct for single tabular model at 100ms P99",
      "LightGBM/XGBoost is the right model family for structured delivery features",
      "Blue-green model deployment with metadata-based rollback",
      "Feature Store shared kernel is non-negotiable for skew prevention",
      "Team split: ML engineers on training path, platform engineers on serving path"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact feature set — needs ML experimentation to determine which features actually improve accuracy",
      "Redis vs in-process cache trade-off for courier load — depends on how many API instances and how dynamic the load data is",
      "Whether weekly retraining is frequent enough — depends on delivery pattern volatility which we haven't measured"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Traffic volume is moderate (thousands of predictions/minute, not millions) — if scale is 10x higher, would recommend Rust-based serving",
      "Model is a single global model, not per-zone or per-city — if zone-specific models are needed, Model Registry design needs extension",
      "Weather and courier load data are available via existing internal APIs or third-party services",
      "The team has Python ML experience (LightGBM, pandas, scikit-learn)"
    ]
  }
}

